<p><i>He went to the Sci-Fi shelf—and had another shock. </i>I, Robot<i> was there, but </i>not<i> the forgettable action movie with Will Smith—this was older, and the credits said “written by Harlan Ellison.” But Ellison’s adaptation of the Isaac Asimov book had never been produced, though it </i>had<i> been published in book form. “Must be some bootleg student production,” he muttered, and he didn’t recognize the name of the production company. But—but—it said “winner of the Academy Award for Best Adapted Screenplay.” That </i>had<i> to be a student director’s little joke, straight-facedly absurd box copy, as if this were a film from some alternate reality. Worth watching, certainly, though again, he couldn’t imagine how he’d never heard of this. Maybe it had been done by someone local. He took it to the counter and offered his credit card.</i></p>

<p><i>She looked at the card dubiously. “Visa? Sorry, we only take Weber and FosterCard.”</i></p>

